00:01.180 --> 00:07.720
This is Daryl Lane. And this is Bill Vernon. And we'll be talking with some
prominent authors about the New Wave and science fiction. The New Wave, which

00:07.720 --> 00:15.960
began in the mid-1960s, was simply a new way of writing science fiction. Yes,
and that newness was seen in many areas. There was often something unusual, for

00:15.960 --> 00:23.080
instance, about the style. Character and psychology were given much more
emphasis. And also the New Wave treated themes, such as sex and religion, that

00:23.080 --> 00:29.640
science fiction hadn't really touched before. Right. And the authors who wrote
about these themes were interested in changing the traditional science fiction

00:29.640 --> 00:38.340
formulas, which had been around since the pulp era of the 1920s, 30s, and 40s.
You know that type of story. It's one in which science is glorified and the hero

00:38.340 --> 00:47.660
rescues Earth from hordes of menacing, bug-eyed monsters. Frederik Pohl, who's
been an author, an editor, and an agent in the field of science fiction, has a

00:47.660 --> 00:57.620
few things to say about that change. The New Wave was an attempt, I guess, 15
years ago or more, of a number of writers to break away from the traditional

00:57.620 --> 01:05.060
kinds of science fiction. In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science
fiction anymore. They wanted to call it speculative fiction or call it nothing

01:05.060 --> 01:16.640
at all. And they were interested primarily in writing about inner space rather
than outer space. And secondarily, a lot of them in things like the drug culture

01:16.640 --> 01:28.860
and rock music and so on. But in the rather bitter internal struggle that went
on in science fiction, a lot of people take sides one way or the other. I think

01:28.860 --> 01:37.360
everyone was deeply affected. We need to remember here that the New Wave wasn't
really a planned and deliberate movement by a unified group of writers. One of

01:37.360 --> 01:45.620
the principal proponents of the New Wave, author Norman Spinrad, believes it was
just a bunch of diverse writers doing their own thing. It was an old wave, but

01:45.620 --> 01:53.200
there was never, as a coherent philosophy in the school of science fiction, but
there was never a New Wave in the same sense. There were a lot of waves. There

01:53.200 --> 02:00.380
were a lot of different people doing a lot of different things. The people that
were identified as the New Wave were very diverse. I mean, what I was actually

02:00.380 --> 02:11.360
writing, it's very different to say what Tom Dish was writing, or Ballard, or
Zelazny, Delaney, or also identified as New Wave writers. This stuff is much

02:11.360 --> 02:22.100
more, you know, Zelazny, and Delaney, and myself, and Ballard, and Aldiss, and
Mike. We were all, there were more differences between our work than between our

02:22.100 --> 02:31.520
work taken into totality and the old stuff. There was more difference within the
so-called New Wave than there was within the so-called old wave. But Spinrad

02:31.520 --> 02:39.000
also thinks the New Wave was tightly connected to what was happening in society.
And of course, this mirrored the cultural climate at the time. It mirrored what

02:39.000 --> 02:46.740
was happening politically. It mirrored what was happening in music. It mirrored
what was happening in movies. It was a phenomenon that went through the Western

02:46.740 --> 02:56.240
civilization as a whole. Some authors maintain that the New Wave is now dead.
Five-time Hugo winner Larry Niven, the author of Ringworld, thinks there's a

02:56.240 --> 03:10.280
good reason for its demise. The New Wave is a very persuasive thing. And very
easy to use to justify bad stories. I think that's what killed it. Not that

03:10.280 --> 03:24.240
increased characterization and experiments with typography and story format are
a bad thing in themselves, but it's so easy to use New Wave to justify a bad

03:24.240 --> 03:26.900
story. It was bound to glass.

03:33.440 --> 03:41.300
That may be so, but lots of others feel that the influence of the New Wave is
still around, though its presence isn't as intense as before. It's left its mark

03:41.300 --> 03:50.080
on the field, no doubt about that. Science fiction has been broadened, maybe
enhanced somehow because of it. Frederik Pohl states it well. And the New Wave,

03:50.180 --> 04:01.580
if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Azimov and Heinlein and
me, that there were non-traditional ways of constructing a novel. See, most

04:01.580 --> 04:09.860
of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazines, and most of
it was written according to some variant of a pulp formula. Well, it turned out

04:09.860 --> 04:15.040
that wasn't necessary. And I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us
that.

