05:26.580 --> 05:34.700
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane and David Carson. Of all the themes handled
by science fiction authors, that of alien contact has been one of the most

05:34.700 --> 05:43.120
consistently popular and fascinating. For a good reason, too. Aliens have always
been one of the biggest attractions of science fiction, whether they be the

05:43.120 --> 05:49.800
hostile bug-eyed monsters of the old pulp magazines or the friendly creatures of
close encounters of the third kind. And they become even more fascinating when

05:49.800 --> 05:57.140
you find them in what some people call a first contact story. First contact, as
the term implies, describes the very first meeting between humans and an alien

05:57.140 --> 06:06.000
species. In the past, stories of alien contact were usually written as
thrillers, with the sole and simple intention of scaring readers. H.G. Wells'

06:06.140 --> 06:13.680
The War of the Worlds is probably the best example of that type of story. But
that's changed. Many contemporary writers have provided more thoughtful

06:13.680 --> 06:21.240
treatments of aliens, deepening the realism and the significance of narratives
of alien contact. Of course, before you can have a story of alien contact, you

06:21.240 --> 06:28.220
must first have some aliens. One of the most provocative descriptions of aliens
in all of science fiction is found in Larry Niven's and Jerry Pournelle's The Mote

06:28.220 --> 06:36.740
in God's Eye, considered by many to be the finest of all first contact stories.
The success of this book is largely due to the unique and ingenious aliens, the

06:36.740 --> 06:45.000
Moties, that Niven created for the story. It's interesting though that Niven
says he doesn't really create aliens for a story, but suggests that it's the

06:45.000 --> 06:59.260
other way around. But I always design aliens for themselves. I almost never
design an alien to match a story. The story, some story will eventually include

06:59.260 --> 07:07.640
the alien. The alien stands for himself. There are two particularly fascinating
things that Niven incorporated into these Moties. One is the fact that they are

07:07.640 --> 07:15.940
not symmetrical. They have a head, torso, legs and arms, as humans do, but the
arms are disproportionate. One is small and thin, and the other is large and

07:15.940 --> 07:26.580
powerful. Right. Niven says he took that idea from studying the structures of
living creatures on Earth. In that case, I had the idea that I was following a

07:26.580 --> 07:40.400
progression with a protozoan, with an amoeba. You get radial symmetry inside and
out. Move up a goodly distance and you find starfishes with radial symmetry on

07:40.400 --> 07:52.200
the outside and bilateral symmetry on the inside. Move up a little further, you
find flat worms and worms of all stents. At the level of bilateral symmetry

07:52.200 --> 08:05.060
inside and out. Go as far as a human, you find bilateral symmetry on the outside
and no symmetry, well, half symmetrical on the inside. The lungs look

08:05.060 --> 08:13.620
symmetrical. The kidneys look symmetrical. The intestines look like somebody
dropped a plate of spaghetti. I tried to move on to the next step.

08:16.960 --> 08:26.760
Bilaterally unsymmetrical on the outside. And I got the original Motie, which
was the engineer's one. The other ingenious idea Niven developed for the Moties

08:26.760 --> 08:34.900
is the way they construct and use machines. They're highly skilled tool users,
but they have no standard pre-manufactured machines, parts, or tools. They

08:34.900 --> 08:42.540
simply alter or reshape whatever they find around them at the time to suit their
needs. And Niven says that particular idea just came to him. It seemed

08:42.540 --> 08:53.840
interesting and even logical. I was just playing with ideas at that point. And
that one seemed like a fun one. It also seemed likely enough. If you've got a

08:53.840 --> 09:08.100
critter with not much intelligence except in the direction of tool making and
tool altering, then why not? The thing has to keep testing its ability or it

09:08.100 --> 09:17.560
will lose it. It might as well be designing something every time it needs a
specific machine. Besides the ingenuity Niven demonstrated in creating the

09:17.560 --> 09:26.660
Moties, he and Pournelle also used some unexpected twists into the first contact
theme. A reader interested in alien contact cannot afford to overlook the moat

09:26.660 --> 09:27.520
in God's eye.

