11:09.360 --> 11:21.680
Even a casual reader of science fiction, if asked to name
his favorite authors, would almost certainly mention the name of Larry Niven.

11:22.460 --> 11:30.420
Niven's popularity rests on a solid and extensive body of work, but one
particular novel seems to have captivated science fiction fans. That casual

11:30.420 --> 11:38.400
reader who named Niven as one of his favorite authors would likely pick
Ringworld as Niven's finest work. The Ringworld is an immense ring, large enough

11:38.400 --> 11:47.120
to hold three million Earths. It has a thousand-mile-high wall on each side to
hold in its atmosphere. It has continents and oceans. The Ringworld contains

11:47.120 --> 11:55.460
trillions of inhabitants of different species and derives energy from the sun at
its center. Niven recalls where he obtained the idea for such a fantastic

11:55.460 --> 12:08.320
structure. Oh, I ran across the concept Dyson sphere. Dyson, the mathematician,
came up with the concept Dyson shell, and he was misunderstood to some extent.

12:08.320 --> 12:21.640
And so presently I ran across an article about Dyson spheres. Picture that as a
golf ball, 93 million miles in radius, with a sun at the center, and gravity

12:21.640 --> 12:34.840
generators all around the outside, so he would live on the inside, terraform it
with oceans and soil and air. I ran across that, and I didn't like it. I thought

12:34.840 --> 12:44.060
it could be improved. And I wound up with the Ringworld. Readers were fascinated
with the Ringworld. So fascinated, in fact, that they studied the science behind

12:44.060 --> 12:53.000
it, and wrote to Niven about what seemed to be errors or inconsistencies in the
theory and design of the immense artifact. Call them errors and elaborations,

12:53.040 --> 13:02.100
because some of them don't really fit the error thing. It's just something that
hadn't gotten into the original book. One of the errors was spotted by some MIT

13:02.100 --> 13:12.380
students. It had to do with the instability of the Ringworld. I suspected the
Ringworld was unstable, and I suspected you'd need attitude jets. I was sure

13:12.380 --> 13:20.600
that the Ringworld was spinning fast enough to permit bizarre dramjets to be
used as attitude jets, which means you don't have a fuel problem at all. You're

13:20.600 --> 13:31.480
burning the solar wind. But rapidly, some MIT people demonstrated that the
Ringworld was unstable, when they were chanting it in the halls at the next

13:31.480 --> 13:35.220
Worldcon. The Ringworld is unstable. The Ringworld is unstable.

13:37.840 --> 13:49.300
It still took about seven years for anyone to figure out the exact numbers for
the instability. And they are horrifying. The Ringworld, a major solar flare

13:49.300 --> 14:01.180
would have the Ringworld grinding against its sun in five years. Well, I worked
it into the plot. That was one elaboration or error. Even teenage readers

14:01.180 --> 14:11.260
analyzed his Ringworld with a critical scientific eye. A high school class in
Florida got to work on the Ringworld. And their conclusion was that the

14:11.260 --> 14:21.240
Ringworld's worst problem is that all the topsoil would wind up in the oceans in
about 3,000 years. There are no earthquakes on the Ringworld. No mountain

14:21.240 --> 14:30.480
building forces. But in a sequel, Ringworld Engineers, Niven attempted to
correct such deficiencies. He devised a way to answer the criticism of the

14:30.480 --> 14:43.280
Florida high schoolers. Okay, that's a tough one. I set up a spill pipe system
that runs the top, that runs the sea bottom muck from the sea bottoms under the

14:43.280 --> 14:59.780
Ringworld and up over the edge of the rim wall. That even allows you some, uh,
some mind accumulation of, uh, useful metals. Fan response of that sort caused

14:59.780 --> 15:06.960
Ringworld Engineers to be written. And although Niven once said he wouldn't
write any more in the Known Space series, the body of stories to which Ringworld

15:06.960 --> 15:19.360
belongs, he's not so sure anymore. I've given up saying that the, uh, that the
Known Space series is dead. There's just no point in it. I've written five books

15:19.360 --> 15:22.160
worth of Known Space stories since I said that.

