17:23.920 --> 17:31.160
Author Larry Niven has produced a body of science fiction that has made him one
of the best-selling authors in the field. A fairly large portion of his work

17:31.160 --> 17:39.440
falls into the known space series, a group of stories and novels with a
consistent chronology and overall evolving pattern to them. Such a series is

17:39.440 --> 17:46.200
called a future history. Niven believes there are some peculiar attractions a
future history has for a science fiction author.

17:49.000 --> 18:03.000
There had been future histories around. Poul Anderson and Robert Heinlein.
I'd say, I guess we've each evolved it somewhat independently, and the idea is

18:04.000 --> 18:17.000
that if you carved out a consistent, workable future, it seems a shame to waste it 
on one story. You put in the background, you want the background of a story

18:14.760 --> 18:22.000
to seem bigger than it is. So there are things that are simply unexplained.

18:25.760 --> 18:35.200
And if you think of more to say on a given subject, why you go with it. And if
you think of a story that fits into the background of a previous story and

18:35.200 --> 18:44.900
allows you to elaborate on that background, sometimes you fall in love with the
background. And presently you've got a bunch of stories that link. Ringworld is

18:44.900 --> 18:52.300
probably the best-known story in Niven's future history, but he's also written
some best-selling books that fall outside his Known Space series. Two of these,

18:52.520 --> 19:01.640
The Mote in God's Eye and Lucifer's Hammer, were written in collaboration with
Jerry Pournelle. Collaboration for a creative writer presents some problems. How

19:01.640 --> 19:13.640
is the work divided up, for instance? Is it hard to decide who writes what? Hard
sometimes, but it always resolves. The question is, who is most qualified to

19:13.640 --> 19:25.100
write a given scene that we have both decided needs writing? Before we start, we
have the novel all laid out. We know what's going in virtually everywhere. And

19:25.100 --> 19:35.400
if we don't, it feels like we do. And if we find out we don't, we elaborate as
we get to that section. Okay, the next question is, who is qualified to write a

19:35.400 --> 19:46.180
given scene? Sometimes it's obvious. If we're dealing with a madman, he's mine.
If we're dealing with military operations, it's Jerry's. Aliens are generally

19:46.180 --> 20:00.280
mine. Politics is generally Jerry's. Knowledge of history is generally Jerry's.
And a real evil son of a bitch, Jerry usually creates him, and I usually run

20:00.280 --> 20:09.460
with him afterwards. But Niven resists classification, either as an author of
future histories or as a collaborator. He sometimes branches out into seldom

20:09.460 --> 20:17.740
entered areas of science fiction. One of these areas is humor, something few
science fiction writers attempt. What does he think his most successful piece of

20:17.740 --> 20:30.760
humor is? I suppose I could name, oh, Man of Steel, Woman of Kleenex, which has
gotten me the most laughs. I suppose everybody seems to have read it, and those

20:30.760 --> 20:39.040
who haven't have heard about it a cocktail party. Niven's ready eye for humor
can also be appreciated as he reveals that he's detected one of his own alien

20:39.040 --> 20:48.820
creations from Ringworld, a disguised Pearson's Puppeteer, here on Earth. I have
reason to suspect the pair of puppeteers on Earth. Look at their

20:48.820 --> 20:58.100
characteristics. Forget the shape. They must be masters of biology to hide that
peculiar three-legged, two-headed shape. But consider their characteristics.

20:58.360 --> 21:09.960
They are cowards. That is, they want everything utterly safe. No corners on
anything. Everything is soft surfaces around the puppeteer world. They don't

21:09.960 --> 21:23.740
even keep their world near a sun. Regarding it as a runaway fusion reactor,
which of course it is. So, desperate regard for safety. Plus an urge to meddle

21:23.740 --> 21:37.580
in the lifestyles of other species. Driving urge to meddle with practically no
restraints attached. What does that remind you of? It seems nearly certain to me

21:37.580 --> 21:39.640
that Ralph Nader is a Pearson's Puppeteer.

